{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c437e87b-ad1d-4459-8adf-12108ea5de93","content":"There are no workflow files in the current directory, so I'll give you the general recipe for switching to NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC):\n\n### 1. Configure your NuGet.org package\n\nOn **nuget.org → Manage Package → Trusted Publishers**, add a GitHub Actions publisher:\n- **Repository owner** / **Repository name**\n- **Workflow filename** (e.g. `publish.yml`)\n- Optionally restrict to an **environment**, **branch**, or **tag pattern**\n\n### 2. Update your GitHub Actions workflow\n\n**Add permissions** to the job:\n\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC token\n  contents: read\n```\n\n**Replace** the `dotnet nuget push` step:\n\n```yaml\n# OLD — remove this\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --api-key ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }} --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n\n# NEW — use trusted publishing\n- uses: dotnet/nuget-push@v1\n  with:\n    source: https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nThe `dotnet/nuget-push` action handles the OIDC token exchange automatically — no API key needed.\n\n### 3. Clean up\n\n- Remove `NUGET_API_KEY` from **Settings → Secrets**.\n\n### Key benefits\n- No long-lived secrets to rotate\n- Push scoped to specific repo/branch/workflow\n- Audit trail tied to the GitHub Actions run\n\nWould you like me to create a sample workflow file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dee04362-2f79-457b-804b-ea0638e632b3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory appears to be empty. The user is asking a general question about switching from NuGet API key to trusted publishing (OIDC). Let me provide guidance based on the general approach since there are no workflow files to examine.","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"6C41:23A25:D233A0:106795A:6A012A2B"},"id":"f09fa64c-5aa5-4dce-a2ed-73810132784a","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:00:38.110Z","parentId":"09c74739-297a-4976-af98-2ef108af769b"}
